observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory at least once a year to strengthen and improve the adequacy of controls on its properties

Consider reorganizing the Inventory Committee by creating sub-committees on a “per account title” basis with counter parts from the Accounting Office. Actual physical count, investigation of differences and reconciliation of balances shall be conducted by the sub-committees to be accomplished within a specific timeline to be set. Accordingly, adjust the appropriate records as warranted and submit a revised RPCPPE based on the reconciliations made;

Direct the Municipal General Service Office to observe the proper inventory taking, naming and property card monitoring of all procured, donated and transferred PPE where the LGU-Itbayat is the rightful owner as prescribed in Chapter 7 of MNGAS for LGUs. Relative to this, all PPE movements (additions/ deductions) shall be promptly communicated with the Accounting Office for proper recording /adjustments in the books;

Direct the Municipal Accounting Office to maintain Ledger Cards for each category of PPE; and

Prioritize the completion of the documentary and procedural requirements of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances and furnish the Audit Team with the necessary documentation.

We recommended that Management:

Include as a priority project the establishment of a room/building which shall serve as the storage facility for procured property and inventories prior to the release to end-user units. Relative to this, Management shall endeavor to maintain a centralized inventory management system;

Require the proper utilization of the stock cards at the office-level in the monitoring of supplies and materials;

Require the Agency’s Inventory Committee together with the representatives from the end-user units and the General Services Officer to conduct an inventory count on all office supplies that are yet to be consumed as of a cut-off date to be determined by the Committee and prepare a Report on Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) for recording and control purposes. Henceforth, conduct the required physical count and submit to the Auditor the report thereon not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;

Based on the RPCI prepared, the Municipal Accountant shall prepare an entry to recognize the cost of Inventories at hand and henceforth observe the proper accounting policies and entries in the recording of transactions; and

Ensure that all properties of the government are properly safeguarded against deterioration, loss and wastage.

We recommended that Management:

Require the implementing offices to propose projects that are well- procurement-and implementation-ready. Henceforth, rigid screening of to be funded out of the 20% DF shall be employed to ensure that only relevant, responsive and feasible items are to be funded and implemented;

Require the Municipal Planning and Development Officer together with the concerned implementing offices, in coordination with the Local Finance Committee, to conduct a periodic review and assessment of the financial and physical status of the programs, projects and activities (PPAs) to determine timely the possible declaration of savings which will be reappropriated for other development projects under the 20% DF, and formulate catch-up plans for slow-moving PPAs to avoid further delays in the implementation;

Require the implementing offices, in coordination with Bids and Awards Committee, to observe the timely procurement activities to ensure prompt delivery of materials and other items necessary in the implementation of PPAs, thus reducing the risk of delayed implementation. Accordingly, Management shall endeavor to conduct early procurement activities pursuant to the provisions of the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR) of Republic Act No. 9184 otherwise known as the Government Procurement Reform Act;

We recommended that Management:

Pending the establishment of a storage room/warehouse, the Municipal Mayor shall designate employees, who shall be properly bonded, to manage the issuance, recording and reporting of inventories in their respective offices;

Direct the Municipal Accountant and Designated GSO to maintain a record of all construction materials on a per project basis, to be regularly reconciled with the records of the Engineering Office. A report on the balance thereon shall be prepared upon the issuance by the Engineering Office of the Certificate of Completion for each successfully completed project; and

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct a complete inventory count of all supplies and materials and submit the corresponding RPCI. Henceforth, the Committee shall ensure the conduct of the required semi-annual physical counts and the timely submission of the RPCI to the COA on or before July 31 and January 31 of each year;
Require the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the RPCI with the accounting records as of the inventory count date and to establish and regularly update the corresponding Supplies Ledger Cards based on inventory movements;
Formally designate supply officers per office through a memorandum outlining their respective roles and responsibilities. As part of their duties, the designated unit supply officers shall consolidate the Requisition and Issue Slips and periodically prepare the SSMI;
Instruct the designated unit supply officers to establish and maintain Stock Cards based on the results of the physical count and to regularly update them for all subsequent inventory movements;
Advise the Municipal Accountant to implement a defined timeline for the submission of SSMIs (whether weekly, bi-weekly or monthly) by the designated supply officers and monitor compliance to ensure accountability and timeliness; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to record purchases upon delivery based on the Acceptance and Inspection Report and other supporting documents such as delivery receipts and charge invoices and to record inventory issuances upon receipt of the periodic SSMIs submitted by the designated supply officers.

We recommended that Management:
Reiterate the previous audit recommendation that requires the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council to review and annually update the LDRRMFIP to ensure that the amount and details of PPAs, which are meticulously and judiciously planned, under the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years are included therein;
Ensure proper coordination between offices, especially those who are involved in the receipt of cash donations, to ensure proper and timely utilization of funds;
Direct the Local Finance Committee and MDRRMO to utilize the balance of the cash donations as at year-end with due consideration on the 1.) conditions attached thereto, if there’s any; 2.) approval of the Sangguniang Bayan, as necessary; and 3.) Work Financial Plan and other necessary supporting documents; and
Continue to monitor the implementation of PPAs to sustain a high utilization rate, thereby strengthening the agency’s capabilities in mitigating, responding, and recovering from the impact of disasters.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to conduct a thorough assessment, evaluation, and investigation of the outstanding accounts and record provision for impairment;

Create a committee that will rigorously pursue the collection of prior year receivables from the identified debtors. Relative to this, Management shall exhaust all possible efforts to collect the receivables such as, but not limited to instituting legal actions against delinquent borrowers, as applicable;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to review the status of the collectability of the dormant receivables and observe the guidelines and procedures on the write-off of Dormant Receivable accounts as prescribed in COA Circular 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016, as necessary; and

Direct the Municipal Social Welfare and Development Office to retrieve copies of the capital assistance granted to SEA-Ks from year 2017 to present and reconcile the same with the accounting office for the preparation of the necessary adjustments to bring the balance of the Loans – receivable account to fair presentation.

We recommended that Management:

Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct the semi-annual physical count of inventories;

Consider reorganizing the Inventory Committee by creating two major committees for PPE accounts and Inventory accounts. Under the Inventory accounts committee, create sub-committees on a “per account title” basis with counterparts from the Accounting Office.
The sub-committees shall undertake the actual physical count, investigation of differences and reconciliation of balances to be accomplished within a specific timeline to be set;

Direct the General Services Officer to submit the RCPI not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the result of the inventory count for the first and second semesters, respectively; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to observe the Perpetual Inventory Method of recording inventories as required under Section 51 of MNGAS-LGUs. Hence, record the purchases of supplies and materials as assets under the specific Inventory Accounts.

We recommended that Management:

Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the appropriate journal entries relative to the unrecorded liabilities totaling ₱418,160.00. Accordingly, working paper adjustment entries shall be prepared for the restatement of the affected accounts to present the correct CY 2023 restated figures in the preparation of the CY 2024 comparative financial statements;

Ensure that goods and services that have been delivered or rendered as at year end be properly recorded as liabilities. Relative to this, require, as year-end cut-off procedures, the MGSO to forward to the MAO all claims for delivered goods and services for the proper recognition of Accounts Payable on the related transactions; 

Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the adjusting entry to correct the various erroneous recordings.; and

Investigate the nature of the long-standing Accounts Payable amounting to ₱1,376,014.40 and revert the same to the unappropriated surplus, as warranted.

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to properly disclose in the Notes to FS the contingent liability arising from the undelivered POs at year-end to ensure the fair presentation of the FS.

We recommended that Management:

Ensure that all PPAs are meticulously and judiciously planned by rigidly screening PPAs to be funded out of the 20% DF especially during the preparation of budget proposal. Accordingly, require the implementing offices to propose projects that are well-planned and procurement-and implementation-ready;

Require the BAC and the Municipal Planning and Development Office (MPDO) to properly plan all its procurement activities, particularly the procurement of infrastructure projects taking into consideration the period of implementation to avoid delays and suspensions;

Advise the MPDO together with the concerned implementing offices, in coordination with the Bids and Awards Committee, to conduct further review of the unimplemented projects under the 20% Development Fund. Formulate/develop specific strategies/ solutions to effectively implement development projects; and

Direct the implementing offices to refrain from proposing projects that are fully composed of labor cost which is contrary to the intent of the Local Government Code. Accordingly, require the reviewing bodies, the Local Finance Committee and the Local Sanggunian, to rigorously evaluate the propriety, composition, accuracy and completeness of each Department’s budget proposals, to ensure that only relevant, responsive and feasible items are to be funded and implemented out of the 20% DF.

We recommended that Management:

Ensure that PPAs funded out of the DRRM funds are well-planned and meticulously reviewed by the LDRRMC. Accordingly, intensive procurement planning and coordination with stakeholders shall be conducted prior to the inclusion of PPAs in the LDRRMP and LDRRMFIP;

Require the implementing office, in coordination with Bid and Awards Committee and Budget Office, to review the reasonableness of PPAs costing to preclude series of failure of bidding, thus expedite the procurement activities and reducing the risk of delayed or non-implementation;

Require the LDRRMC to review and annually update the LDRRMFIP to ensure that the amount and details of PPAs under the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years are included therein;

Reiterate the previous audit recommendation that requires the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all unexpended balance of the LDRRMF for CO shall be made continuing in the General Fund books until the projects funded therefore are completed as prescribed under Item 5.1.11 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012; and

Strictly monitor the implementation of the PPAs to attain 100 percent completion.

We recommended that Management:

Submit explanation/ justification with verifiable basis why disbursements on procurements which were noted as non-compliant with existing procurement law, as mentioned above, should not be suspended/disallowed in post-audit;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursements for the procurement of goods and services are included in the end-user PPMP and Agency APP by requiring a certification to that effect from the Head of the BAC Secretariat, who shall, based on the submissions of the end-user units, validate such fact;

Henceforth, require the BAC to submit the proof of validation on the technical, legal and financial capability of the suppliers together with Mayor’s Permit and proof of PhilGEPs Registration on all purchases made through Alternative Mode of Procurement to support eligibility of suppliers;

Ensure that all regulatory permits, registrations and licenses are available and up-to-date prior to engaging the services of individuals and businesses. If unavailable, encourage the prospective suppliers to secure permits and comply other registration requirements such as Mayor’s Permit, BIR and PhilGEPS registrations etc., to ensure eligibility in future procurement endeavors with the LGU;

Advise the BAC to conduct thorough review of the documents submitted by the bidders on all stages of the procurement process to ensure that contracts are awarded only to qualified bidders with responsive bids; and

Carefully review the most appropriate mode of procurement to be undertaken to promote economy of time and resources.

We recommended that Management:

Ensure that PPAs funded out of the DRRM funds are well-planned and meticulously reviewed by the LDRRMC. Accordingly, intensive procurement planning and coordination with stakeholders shall be conducted prior to the inclusion of PPAs in the LDRRMP and LDRRMFIP;

Strictly monitor its implementation to facilitate the timely completion thereof;

Require the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction Management Officer, in coordination with the Local Disaster Reduction Management Council (LDRRMC), to conduct a periodic review and assessment of the financial and physical status of the programs, projects and activities (PPAs) to determine timely the possible declaration of savings which will be reappropriated to finance new or augment existing Disaster Risk Reduction Management PPAs and formulate catch-up plans for slow-moving PPAs to avoid further delays in the implementation;

Require the Local Disaster Reduction Management Council (LDRRMC) to review the existing PPAs under the LDRRMF to determine the relevance and responsiveness of the projects to the present circumstances including the reasonableness of project costing and make the necessary revisions as warranted subject to the appropriate approvals;

Require the Municipal Accounting to ensure that the unexpended/unobligated balance of the LDRRMF for CO shall be made continuing in the General Fund books until the projects funded therefor are completed as prescribed under Item 5.1.11 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012; and

Require the preparer of the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF to religiously observe the timely submission of the report on or before the 15th day after the end of each month and utilize the required format in Annex B as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012.

We recommended that Management:
submit explanation/justification with verifiable basis why disbursements on procurements which were noted as non-compliant with existing procurement law, as mentioned above, should not be suspended/disallowed in post-audit;
require the BAC to submit the proof of validation of eligibility of the suppliers such Mayor’s Permit, proof of PhilGEPs Registration, Income/Business Tax Return (for ABC above P50,000.00) and Omnibus Sworn Statement (for ABC above P50,000.00) on all purchases made through Negotiated Procurement to support eligibility of suppliers;
henceforth, require the submission of BAC resolution recommending award of contract to the supplier with lowest quotation which complies with the specifications and other terms and conditions stated in the Request for Quotation (RFQ) as additional basis of the Head of Agency to enter into contract with the said supplier;
direct the BAC Secretariat to ensure that posting requirements of RFQ, Notice of Award, Purchase Order/Contract and Notice to Proceed if necessary, on all negotiated procurement modality with ABC higher than P50,000.00 are complied with and proof thereof are attached to the disbursement voucher to establish correctness of information and reliability of bidding process;
direct the BAC Secretariat to prepare and send RFQs/RFPs to at least three (3) suppliers, contractors or consultants of known qualifications;
direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to withhold the total amount of P28,773.08 from the identified suppliers representing liquidated damages and henceforth strictly monitor the timeliness of deliveries for possible imposition thereof;
direct the Inspection Officer and the Property Officer, based on verifiable evidence, to identify the actual dates of deliveries of the goods with incomplete details in the Purchase Orders(POs) and/or Acceptance and Inspection Reports (AIRs) as identified;
based on the information to be obtained from the Inspection Officer and the Property Officer, the Municipal Accountant shall ascertain on a per PO basis, whether or not delay in the delivery of procured items exists, compute the applicable liquidated damages thereon, as warranted and withhold the same from the future payments to the identified suppliers;
direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursements for the procurement of goods and services are included in the end-user PPMP and Agency APP by requiring a certification to that effect from the Head of the BAC Secretariat, who shall, based on the submissions of the end-user units, validate such fact; and
require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all essential information are provided in the supporting documents to establish the validity and legality of the transactions.
Management, through the BAC Chairman, assured compliance with our recommendations. Accordingly, the identified lacking documents shall be transmitted to the Office of the Auditor.
While we appreciate Management’s commitment to implement our recommendations, we shall validate compliance thereof in CY 2022.

We recommended the following courses of actions:
The Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accountant and General Services Office with the complete description and cost segregation of road component for road projects;
The GSO or inventory team submit Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network (RPCLRN);
The GSO and Municipal Accountant maintain the required Local Road Network Property and Ledger Cards, respectively.
The Accounting Office prepares the Journal Voucher to record the local road network and its component in the books of accounts.

